                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#k">Time by the Stars.</hi>
                </head>
                <p>&#x2014;The two large stars (says<lb break="yes"/>Humboldt) which indicate the summit and foot of the<lb break="yes"/>cross, having nearly the same right ascension (about<lb break="yes"/>185 degrees, or 12h. 20m.), the constellation must<lb break="yes"/>necessarily be nearly in a vertical direction at the in-<lb break="no"/>stant when it passes the meridian. This circumstance<lb break="yes"/>is well known by all the people who live beyond the<lb break="yes"/>tropic, or in the southern hemisphere. They have<lb break="yes" />noticed at what period of the night, in different sea-<lb break="no"/>sons, the southern cross is upright, or inclined to the<lb break="yes"/>horizon. The constellation thus serves as a clock,<lb break="yes"/>gaining, with perfect regularity, about four minutes<lb break="yes"/>in a day: and there is no other group of stars which<lb break="yes"/>afford at a glance so obvious and easy an observation<lb break="yes"/>of the time. How often have we heard our guides<lb break="yes"/>exclaim, in the wild savannahs of Venezuela, or in<lb break="yes"/>the desert which stretches from Lima to Truxillo, &#x201C;It<lb break="yes"/>is past midnight, the cross begins to turn.&#x201D; How<lb break="yes"/>often have those words recalled to our minds the<lb break="yes" />touching scene in which Paul and Virginia hold their<lb break="yes"/>last interview, and the old man reminds them, on ob-<lb break="no"/>serving the position of the southern cross, that it is<lb break="yes"/>time for them to separate.&#x2014;<hi rendition="#i">Christian Mother&#x2019;s Ma-<lb break="no"/>gazine.</hi>
                </p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
